{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489651"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:24:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:24:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"710"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/710"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.01,0.13,0.75,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"710"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78124"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/710"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"710"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63546"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"131"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"2141"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"648"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3681"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39416"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78124"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man presents to review on the neurosurgical ward with acute confusion and headache. He is five days post open surgical clipping of a ruptured anterior communicating artery aneurysm. His recovery had been uncomplicated until now, with Glasgow Coma Scale 15 and no focal neurological deficits. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears drowsy. His pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 135/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He is disoriented to time and place. There is a new left-sided facial droop and 4/5 weakness of the left upper limb. Laboratory investigations from this morning are within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urgent ventriculostomy","Electroencephalogram","Magnetic resonance angiography","CT angiography with perfusion","Transcranial doppler ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with neurological deterioration in the typical \u0027vasospasm window\u0027 (3-10 days) following aneurysmal subarachnoid haemorrhage. The combination of reduced consciousness, new focal neurological deficits, and headache is highly suspicious for delayed cerebral ischaemia secondary to vasospasm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiography with perfusion\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial investigation as it can rapidly identify or exclude several potential complications including vasospasm, hydrocephalus, re-bleeding, and new ischaemic events. The perfusion maps are particularly useful in identifying areas of compromised cerebral blood flow that may benefit from intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranscranial doppler ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is sometimes used for screening asymptomatic patients for vasospasm but is not the most appropriate first-line investigation when clinical deterioration has already occurred. While it can be performed at the bedside, it is less sensitive and specific than CT perfusion studies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance angiography\u003C/strong\u003E provides detailed vascular imaging but is more time-consuming and less readily available than CT. It offers little additional benefit over CT perfusion in the acute setting when rapid diagnosis is essential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectroencephalogram\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if seizure activity was suspected and imaging had not revealed an alternative cause. However, the focal neurological deficits and timing make vasospasm more likely than seizure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent ventriculostomy\u003C/strong\u003E is a therapeutic rather than diagnostic intervention. While it would be indicated if imaging demonstrated acute hydrocephalus, it should not be performed without first establishing the cause of deterioration through appropriate imaging.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neurological deterioration 3-10 days after subarachnoid haemorrhage should raise high suspicion for cerebral vasospasm","CT angiography with perfusion mapping is the first-line investigation for suspected vasospasm as it can rapidly assess multiple potential complications","The classic presentation of vasospasm includes new focal neurological deficits, reduced consciousness, and headache"],"references":["Ivanidze J, Sanelli PC. Vasospasm: Role of Imaging in Detection and Monitoring Treatment. Neuroimaging Clin N Am. 2021 May;31(2):147-155. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33902870/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63546"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"710"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63546"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T14:02:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-12T19:06:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"710"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78124"}}},"meta":{"canDele